  whatItMeans: {
    en: "New York's Stop Hacks and Improve Electronic Data Security Act — the SHIELD Act — is General Business Law 899-aa and 899-bb. It sets two core duties.\n\nBreach notification (899-aa). Any person or business that owns or licenses computerized data with private information of New York residents has to notify affected residents without unreasonable delay after discovering a breach. The notice has to describe what happened, the categories of information exposed, contact information for the business, and contact information for the major credit bureaus. When more than 500 New York residents are affected, the business also has to notify the Attorney General, the Department of State, and the Division of State Police.\n\nWhat counts as 'private information'. The SHIELD Act covers a broader list than many state breach laws. It includes: a Social Security number; a driver's license or non-driver ID number; a financial account number with any code that would allow access to the account; biometric data such as fingerprints or voice prints; a username or email address paired with a password or a security question and answer; and a credit or debit card number (in combination with a required security code in some cases). A stand-alone email address with no password is not enough to trigger notification — but an email paired with a login credential is.\n\nReasonable security (899-bb). The SHIELD Act requires every business handling New York residents' private information to implement reasonable administrative, technical, and physical safeguards. The law gives small-business examples of what 'reasonable' looks like: designating an employee for security, identifying risks, training staff, encrypting sensitive data, and disposing of old data securely. A business that fails to maintain reasonable security can be investigated and fined by the Attorney General under 899-bb.\n\nNo private right of action. The SHIELD Act itself does not give individuals the right to sue a company for a breach. When a breach causes actual harm — identity theft, fraudulent accounts, drained savings — other laws can support a claim. Common paths include: consumer fraud under General Business Law 349, negligence theories, and class-action lawsuits when many people are affected.\n\nSteps after a breach. The usual protective steps, all free, are: (1) place a credit freeze at Equifax, Experian, and TransUnion; (2) add a one-year fraud alert (extending to seven years with a police report); (3) file an identity theft report at identitytheft.gov for the FTC record that simplifies disputes later; (4) change passwords on any account that uses a credential pattern shown in the breach; and (5) monitor statements for unusual activity. The letter from the company often includes an offer of free credit monitoring — useful, but not a substitute for a credit freeze.\n\nChildren's information. When a breach exposes a child's Social Security number, placing a child credit freeze is separate from an adult freeze. Each bureau has a distinct child-freeze process, usually requiring mailed identity documents.\n\nFederal layers. HIPAA governs breaches of health information held by covered health care entities. The Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act and state financial rules apply to banks and insurers. Federal and state laws can both apply to the same breach. Employers that hold W-2 records are covered by the SHIELD Act as well.\n\nComplaints. When a company fails to notify, delays unreasonably, or downplays the scope of a breach, a complaint can be filed with the NYS Attorney General's Internet and Technology Bureau."
  },

